               <desc type="building-data" xml:lang="en">
                  <p source="#bibl000210-1" xml:lang="en">The Moni Hall is located north of the <placeName ref="/keyword/000064b">Dajue liushi Hall</placeName> foundation and would have been the third timber-frame structure on the central axis. Based on a craftsman’s inscription discovered during a recent renovation from 1976 to 1980, we know it was originally completed during the <term ref="/keyword/k000074">Northern Song dynasty</term>, in the year 1052 (Guo 2009, 370).</p>
                  <p source="#bibl000210-1" xml:lang="en">Despite renovations throughout its history, its core <term ref="/keyword/k000130">diantang</term> style structure largely retains the style of the <term ref="/keyword/k000074">Song dynasty</term> original. It is now the largest building surviving in the <placeName ref="/keyword/000064">Longxing Monastery</placeName> complex. It is seven bays wide and seven bays deep, measuring 33.29 meters wide and 27.12 meters deep. It has a double-eaves <term subtype="keyword" ref="/keyword/k000143">xieshan</term> roof and the major bracket sets are Song Dynasty originals in five <term ref="/keyword/k000013">puzuo</term>, with the first outward step in "stolen-heart" (<term ref="/keyword/k000024">touxin 偷心</term>) style (Guo 2009, 373-375).</p>
                  <p source="#bibl000210-1" xml:lang="en">The intercolumnar and corner bracket sets have two extra huagong in the 45-degree position respective to the wall plane (Guo 2009, 378). This type of bracket arm is also called a <term ref="/keyword/k000148">xiegong 斜栱</term>. Moni Hall hosts a sculptural program including Sakyamuni framed by Manjusri and Samantabhadra on the main altar. On the opposite side of this altar, facing northward, is a sculpture of "Avalokitesvara on an Island in the Sea" (Haidao Guanyin 海島觀音) dated to 1563 (Guojia wenwuju 2013, 37).</p>
                  <p source="#bibl000210-1" xml:lang="zh-Hant">摩尼殿為<placeName ref="/keyword/000064">隆興寺</placeName>中軸線上第三座主要木構建築。 1976年至1980間，該殿進行了落架重修，於重修工程中發現<term ref="/keyword/k000074">宋</term>皇祐四年（1052）的題記，證實了摩尼殿為該年所建（Guo 2009, 370）。</p>
                  <p source="#bibl000210-1" xml:lang="zh-Hant">盡管摩尼殿經明，<term ref="/keyword/k000070">清</term>二代多次重修，其殿堂構架大體保留了宋代始建時的面貌。摩尼殿面闊七間，寬33.29米，進深七間，深27.12米，為隆興寺中現存規模最大的建築。其為重簷<term subtype="keyword" ref="/keyword/k000143">歇山</term>頂，四面正中各出山面向外的<term>歇山</term>頂<term>抱廈</term>。<term ref="/keyword/k000019">枓栱</term>為五鋪作<term ref="/keyword/k000024">偷心造</term>，大體分為單梢單下昂與出雙梢的兩種類型（Guo 2009, 373-5）。</p>
                  <p source="#bibl000210-1" xml:lang="zh-Hant">其中補間鋪作與柱頭鋪作中以45度華栱為殿的特徵（Guo 2009, 378）。這類栱也被稱為<term ref="/keyword/k000148">斜栱</term>。摩尼殿主要供奉華嚴三聖，阿彌陀佛，文殊菩薩，普賢菩薩，現存為宋塑原作（国家文物局 2013, 37）。</p>
